                <h2>Introduction: Why CAC Has Become the Lifeline of Game Publishing</h2>
<blockquote>
<p>"In the gaming industry, every 10% increase in Customer Acquisition Cost could mean a 30%+ compression in overall profits." — This is not an exaggeration but a reality validated by countless publishers with real money.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>In 2024, global mobile gaming competition has intensified, and traffic costs on major advertising platforms (Meta, Google, TikTok) continue to rise. According to AppsFlyer's "State of Mobile Gaming Marketing 2024" report, the average CAC for gaming apps globally has increased by approximately 23% in the past year, with casual games showing the most significant rise at 28%. For game publishers, <strong>deeply understanding and optimizing acquisition costs</strong> has become a core capability determining business success or failure.</p>
<p>This article provides a comprehensive CAC analysis report based on real-world data from multiple first-tier publishing projects, covering market comparisons, game genre analysis, factor breakdowns, and practical optimization strategies.</p>
<hr />
<h2>Part 1: CAC Definition and Correct Calculation Methods</h2>
<h3>What is CAC?</h3>
<p>CAC (Customer Acquisition Cost) refers to the average cost required to acquire one new user. The formula seems simple:</p>
<p><strong>CAC = Total Ad Spend ÷ New Users Acquired</strong></p>
<p>However, in actual operations, many teams oversimplify CAC understanding. True CAC analysis requires distinguishing these dimensions:</p>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>CAC Type</th>
<th>Definition</th>
<th>Application Scenario</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td><strong>Raw CAC</strong></td>
<td>Ad spend ÷ Total new users</td>
<td>Initial budget allocation</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><strong>Paid CAC</strong></td>
<td>Ad spend ÷ Paying users</td>
<td>Commercial efficiency evaluation</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><strong>Retention CAC</strong></td>
<td>Ad spend ÷ 7-day retained users</td>
<td>Channel quality assessment</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><strong>LTV-adjusted CAC</strong></td>
<td>Ratio of CAC to user lifetime value</td>
<td>Overall health judgment</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<h3>The Golden Formula for CAC and ROI</h3>
<p><strong>ROI = LTV ÷ CAC × 100%</strong></p>
<p>A healthy game publishing project typically requires an <strong>LTV/CAC ratio ≥ 3</strong>, meaning user lifetime value should be at least 3 times the acquisition cost. Below this threshold means your user acquisition business is burning money rather than making it.</p>
<hr />
<h2>Part 2: 2024 Mainstream Market CAC Comparative Analysis</h2>
<h3>North America: High Cost, High Reward</h3>
<p>The North American market remains the "golden battlefield" for global game advertising. Although CAC is highest, user quality and monetization capability are also the strongest.</p>
