<h2>Part 5: CAC Optimization Practical Strategies (With Detailed Data)</h2>
<h3>Strategy 1: Scientific Approach to Creative Iteration</h3>
<p>Many teams create creatives by "gut feeling." The correct approach is to <strong>establish a systematic creative testing framework</strong>:</p>
<pre><code>Weekly tests: 5-8 new creative sets
Per creative budget: $50-100 (for rapid validation)
Passing criteria: CTR &gt; 1.5%, CVR &gt; 30%
Scale-up conditions: CTR &gt; 2%, CVR &gt; 35%
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Case Study</strong>: An RPG game improved its quality creative proportion from 12% to 38% through 3 months of systematic creative testing, reducing overall CAC by 27%.</p>
<h3>Strategy 2: Attribution Window Optimization</h3>
<p>Different attribution windows significantly affect "apparent" CAC values:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>7-day attribution window</strong>: Lower CAC, but may include low-quality users</li>
<li><strong>1-day attribution window</strong>: Higher CAC, but user quality is more guaranteed</li>
</ul>
<blockquote>
<p>💰 <strong>Financial Impact</strong>: Adjusting attribution window from 7 days to 1 day may increase CAC by 15%-20%, but <strong>LTV-adjusted true CAC may actually decrease</strong> because delayed-attributed low-quality users are filtered out.</p>
</blockquote>
<h3>Strategy 3: Dynamic Bidding and Budget Adjustment</h3>
<p>Don't "set it and forget it." Conduct daily checks:</p>
<ol>
<li><strong>Ad sets with cost overruns &gt;15%</strong>: Lower bid or pause</li>
<li><strong>Cost on target but insufficient volume</strong>: Appropriately increase bid 10%-20%</li>
<li><strong>Well-performing ad sets</strong>: Gradually scale and observe cost inflection points</li>
</ol>
<h3>Strategy 4: Retargeting</h3>
<p>Already-installed but non-converted users cost only 40%-60% of new user acquisition:</p>
